{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"482"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/482"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.11,0.08,0.07,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70438"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1947"},{"type":"tags","id":"2806"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70438"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive shortness of breath on exertion. He has chronic back pain associated with morning stiffness lasting more than one hour that improves with activity. He has no significant medical history and takes oral diclofenac as needed for back pain. He smokes 20 cigarettes per day with a 10 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is no jugular venous distension. Chest examination reveals normal vesicular breath sounds without added sounds. Heart sounds are normal. His erythrocyte sedimentation rate is 64 mm/hr (0-20).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pulmonary function test patterns would be most likely in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco","FEV1/FVC 65% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco","FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco","FEV1/FVC 65% predicted, normal TLC, increased DLco","FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, reduced TLC, reduced DLco"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s history strongly suggests ankylosing spondylitis (AS) with inflammatory back pain, morning stiffness improving with activity, and elevated inflammatory markers. While AS can be associated with interstitial lung disease (ILD), the normal breath sounds on examination make this less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC 85% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely pattern. The reduced total lung capacity (TLC) reflects restriction from decreased chest wall mobility due to costovertebral joint involvement in AS. The normal diffusing capacity (DLco) helps differentiate this from parenchymal lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC 65% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the pattern seen in emphysema, with airflow obstruction, hyperinflation, and reduced gas transfer. While this patient smokes, he is young with a relatively short smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC 85% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco\u003C/strong\u003E would be an unusual combination not typically seen in any common respiratory condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC 65% predicted, normal TLC, increased DLco\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in asthma, but there is no history of wheeze or variable airflow obstruction to suggest this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC 85% predicted, reduced TLC, reduced DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the pattern seen in ILD. While AS can be associated with ILD, the normal breath sounds make this less likely in this case. ILD typically presents with fine crackles on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to this question is recognising that the restrictive defect in AS is primarily due to mechanical limitation of chest wall movement rather than a primary lung pathology, hence the preserved DLco. This distinguishes it from other causes of restriction such as ILD where the DLco is typically reduced.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ankylosing spondylitis commonly causes restrictive lung disease due to reduced chest wall mobility","While ankylosing spondylitis can be associated with interstitial lung disease, normal breath sounds make this less likely","Normal DLco helps differentiate chest wall restriction from parenchymal lung disease"],"references":["Schwartzstein R. Chest wall diseases and restrictive physiology. In: UptoDate, Post TW (Ed), Waltham, MA: UptoDate; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"482"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T12:19:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T12:22:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70438"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position